Tasks:

Either read in the data using the code below (need to install googlesheets4 library if you dont have it) or download from this URL and put it in your project folder.

bestsellers <- read_sheet("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1n3xKHK4-t5S73LgxOJVJWT5fMYjLj7kqmYl1LHkpk80/edit?usp=sharing")
## Reading from "bestsellers"
## Range "bestsellers"

BE SURE TO REMOVE eval=FALSE from all code sections.

  1. Find books with multiple authors (HINT: Consider the possibility of an author having and in their name)
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(mult_auth = str_detect(author, "\\sand\\s")) %>% 
  filter(mult_auth == "TRUE") %>% 
  summarize(title, author, mult_auth)
  1. Detect if the authors first name starts with a vowel
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(vowel = str_detect(author, "^[AEIOU]")) %>% 
  filter(vowel == "TRUE") %>% 
  summarize(author, vowel)
  1. Change all authors with the name Alexander to Alex
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(names = str_replace_all(author, "Alexander", "Alex"))
  1. Find books that are the second book in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                             pattern = "sequel")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)
  1. Find books that are the third or fourth one in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                          pattern = "(third|fourth) book")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)
  1. Find books that are the 10th, 11th, , or 19th book in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                          pattern = "1[0-9]th book")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)

tmap exercises

Read in the data:

data("World")

In addition to the World data, we will use data called metro that comes from the tmap package. It contains metropolitan area information from major cities across the globe. Some important variables include:

  • Name : city name
  • pop2010 : population in 2010
  • pop2020 : population in 2020
data("metro")

!!!!!!REMEMBER TO REMOVE eval=FALSE!!!!!!!!!!!

  1. Make a world map using the base World dataset we used with the COVID example. Add information about income groups (income_grp) to the plot, specify a color palette.
# let's explore the variable names of each dataset
names(World)
names(metro)
tmap_mode('plot')
## tmap mode set to plotting
tm_shape(World) +
    tm_polygons("income_grp", 
                palette="-Blues", 
                contrast= .5, 
                id="name", 
                title="Income group")

  1. To the plot from (1), add the new dataset metro to the plot, and add information about cities populations in 2020.
tmap_mode('plot')
## tmap mode set to plotting
tm_shape(World) +
    tm_polygons("income_grp", palette="-Blues", contrast= .5, id="name", title="Income group") +
  tm_shape(metro) +
  tm_bubbles("pop2020")

  1. Now, make a new plot with the World data that provides a look at country economic status and the inequality associated with each.
# Set your mode
tmap_mode('plot')
## tmap mode set to plotting
tm_shape(World) +
  tm_polygons("economy") +
  tm_bubbles("inequality", border.alpha = .5) +
  tm_format("World_wide")

  1. Using a new data set, NDL_muni municipality data from the Netherlands, create a plot with two separate maps. One showing the percentage of men per municipality of the whole country, and one showing the same but faceted by province.
tmap_mode("plot")
## tmap mode set to plotting
data(NLD_muni)

NLD_muni$perc_men <- NLD_muni$pop_men / NLD_muni$population * 100

tm1 <- tm_shape(NLD_muni) + tm_polygons("perc_men", palette = 'RdYlBu')

tm2 <- tm_shape(NLD_muni) +
    tm_polygons("perc_men", palette = "RdYlBu") +
    tm_facets(by = "province")

tmap_arrange(tm1, tm2)

Data Ethics: Data visualization principles

Im hoping that the topic for this week is a review for all of you, but its good to remind ourselves of these principles.

Task:

Read both short articles in Week6. Data visualization section of Calling Bulllshit. Were there any principles mentioned that you hadnt heard of before? What graph stood out for you as the worst? Did any of the graphs fool you? Or were able to overcome the bad practices (dont worry if they fool you - plently of them have fooled me, too.)? How does practicing good data visualization principles fit in with data ethics?

An interesting idea what that line charts dont need to start at zero on the dependent axis. I kinda always thought there should be a zero there to provide context. But after reading I realized that what matters is the trend you are trying to show and the fact that it goes down to zero doesnt matter. Gun deaths in Florida gets me every time because of how bad it is. Its the worst and fooled me. Data vis and ethics go hand in hand because you want to produce results that are easy to understand for all parties, and that dont fool or mess with your audience intentionally. Most people will glance at a graph once and live with that take away forever so it is important that on first glance the point comes across correctly.
